{"title":"Weight loss drugs","img":"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/images/ic/1200xn/p0n8fq0r.jpg","url":"https://www.bbc.co.uk/learningenglish/english/features/6-minute-english_2026/ep-260326","audio":"https://downloads.bbc.co.uk/learningenglish/features/6min/260326_6_minute_english_weight_loss_drugs_download_.mp3","intro":["Weight loss drugs like Ozempic and Mounjaro are modified versions of natural hormones which make us feel full when released into the body. Prof Giles Yeo explains how the drugs, which were originally used to treat diabetes, are now being used for weight loss. We also hear about someone's experience of using the drugs. Georgie and Neil teach you some useful vocabulary."],"this_week_question":["The measurement used by doctors to estimate if someone is at a healthy weight is called BMI. But what does BMI stand for? Is it:","a) British medical index? b) Body mass index? or, c) Body muscle index?","Listen to the programme to hear the answer."],"vocab":[{"text":"food noise","desc":"intrusive, unwanted thoughts about food"},{"text":"into the ether","desc":"(idiom) completely disappeared; vanished into the air"},{"text":"an angel on one shoulder and a devil on the other","desc":"(idiom) used to describe a personal dilemma or difficult decision based on an imaginary angel, representing conscience, and an imaginary devil, representing temptation"},{"text":"self-esteem","desc":"belief and confidence in your own abilities"},{"text":"on the market","desc":"available for sale"},{"text":"side effect","desc":"secondary effect of a drug or medicine, usually undesirable or unwanted"}],"transcript":[{"author":"Neil","text":"Hello. This is 6 Minute English from BBC Learning English. I'm Neil."}],"authors":["Neil"],"wave_peaks":[3201,6857,7374,22467,20713,19946,13673,17008,10872,20228,14531,14220,15053,13808,11934,17113,12961,7739,1998,1830,1730,988,958,959,942,44,14622,12927,12757,12207,14361,12667,17606,8277,7400,12114,5088,2810,8542,10281,9747,8360,9385,7498,4050,5546,